<img srcset="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/Ax2najJDU6-j7S2TVvftU899abQ=/0x0:5245x3496/320x0/filters:focal(0x0:5245x3496):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19857911/GettyImages_1208510610.jpg 320w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/GU4Qk47YJQTlJ8gRxRJ3SzqB74g=/0x0:5245x3496/520x0/filters:focal(0x0:5245x3496):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19857911/GettyImages_1208510610.jpg 520w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/50hvQGsKmldkWK1i71TME38LNpc=/0x0:5245x3496/720x0/filters:focal(0x0:5245x3496):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19857911/GettyImages_1208510610.jpg 720w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/MluqKDB1ymh6Rms7ITX8UTHi0Es=/0x0:5245x3496/920x0/filters:focal(0x0:5245x3496):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19857911/GettyImages_1208510610.jpg 920w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/XMw15Bl5AKaGrw2YTRj6JQ-pd9Y=/0x0:5245x3496/1120x0/filters:focal(0x0:5245x3496):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19857911/GettyImages_1208510610.jpg 1120w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/1Sw6E11xNn8ls7wHVdtzFbcmO24=/0x0:5245x3496/1320x0/filters:focal(0x0:5245x3496):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19857911/GettyImages_1208510610.jpg 1320w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/hOozOTm4ocCb0SF8i2HkT5lUl4I=/0x0:5245x3496/1520x0/filters:focal(0x0:5245x3496):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19857911/GettyImages_1208510610.jpg 1520w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/W0XIv2k5oea4jRo6a3SeEk4Q_K4=/0x0:5245x3496/1720x0/filters:focal(0x0:5245x3496):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19857911/GettyImages_1208510610.jpg 1720w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/BbRGRIu2IgKysvWeikp4HVNO1No=/0x0:5245x3496/1920x0/filters:focal(0x0:5245x3496):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19857911/GettyImages_1208510610.jpg 1920w" sizes="(min-width: 1221px) 846px, (min-width: 880px) calc(100vw - 334px), 100vw" alt="" data-upload-width="5245" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/B8-r3fu1SD0xQXa4ukS6nX3fuUE=/0x0:5245x3496/1200x0/filters:focal(0x0:5245x3496):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19857911/GettyImages_1208510610.jpg">

</source></picture>

      
    </span>
    
  </span>
  
    <span class="e-image__meta">
      
        <figcaption>Workers set up a field hospital in front of Mount Sinai West Hospital inside Central Park in New York City on March 29.</figcaption>
      
      
        <cite>Kena Betancur/AFP via Getty Images</cite>
      
    </span>
  
</figure>

<p id="tRXT0k">We are already poised to begin significant fiscal stimulus, and that has helped. But to get to where we need to be, we need to do even more — put more cash into state and local government coffers, cut taxes on individuals and businesses, put money directly into the hands of the American people, and finance increased production of medical and household cleaning supplies. </p>
<p id="8a0LE7">A program like that won’t eliminate the economic costs of coronavirus. Huge amounts of labor will be “wasted” on cleaning and re-cleaning surfaces, and manufacturing supplies that are swiftly used up and thrown away rather than building wealth. But it will avoid mass unemployment, cascading waves of bankruptcies, and the other miseries associated with a depression. And since the economic problems will be genuinely virus-related, they will go away whenever the medical situation improves — whether that’s because of improved testing, improved treatments, new findings that it’s not as deadly as we feared, or whatever else.</p>
<p id="x8ykzb">The problem with the demand shock is that it is currently bigger in economic terms than the supply-side impacts of the virus itself. And — because it’s caused by policy failure rather than RNA strands replicating in our cells — there’s no guarantee it goes away, even if there is a totally effective vaccine a year from now.</p>
<p id="PvIBTX">It’s time for economic policymakers to let the doctors, epidemiologists, and other public health officials do their jobs, and to start taking responsibility for doing their own work instead. The virus is a fact we have to deal with. The ongoing collapse in aggregate demand is a policy choice we can avoid. </p>
<hr class="p-entry-hr" id="zwNUNh">
<h3 id="hHEd6O">Listen to <em>The Weeds</em>
</h3>
